I found these snippets:
<details>
<summary>https://psalm.dev/r/65d07cb31c</summary>

```php
<?php

/**
 * @psalm-pure
 */
function foo(): callable
{
    return function() {
      echo "bar";
    };
}
```

```
Psalm output (using commit 5f5ce6e):

ERROR: ImpureFunctionCall - 9:7 - Cannot call echo from a mutation-free context
```
</details>

issue.body:
Welcome back to the corner of @Ocramius' tricky issues!

I'm currently designing a system to declare DB mutations in a pure way, and execute them (at runtime) in an impure way. It looks kinda like this:

```php
/** @psalm-pure */
interface MutationDefinition
{
    /** @psalm-return list<callable (Machine) : void> */
    public function effects():array;
}

/** @psalm-pure */
final class StepsToMakeCoffee implements MutationDefinition
{
    /** @psalm-return list<callable (Machine) : void> */
    public function effects():array
    {
        return [
            function (Machine $m) : void { $m->addBeans(); },
            function (Machine $m) : void { $m->grindBeans(); },
            function (Machine $m) : void { $m->addWater(); },
            function (Machine $m) : void { $m->boilWater(); },
            // ... well, you get the point
        ];
    }
}
```

Stripping down everything, we get following meta-code:

```php
/** @psalm-pure */
function makeSomeStuff() : callable
{
    return static function (object $dependency) {
        \var_dump($dependency, 'impure, pure `makeSomeStuff`');
    };
}
```

Psalm rejects this, because, while the method is pure, it does indeed produce closures that have side-effects when run: https://psalm.dev/r/e9a48220fc

 > ERROR: ImpureFunctionCall - 6:9 - Cannot call an impure function from a mutation-free context

In FP langs, this is something like `makeSomeStuff :: [(IO a -> IO ())]` (notice that `makeSomeStuff` is still pure).

This calls for a few things to be tweaked:

 * [ ] the idea of "pure context" should not expand to results of pure contexts. If a function is pure, the produced data structure is immutable, but not necessarily pure (`function (Machine $m) : void { $m->addBeans(); }` is an immutable `Closure`, but `Machine` is not immutable nor pure)
 * [ ] Immutability and purity are not necessarily overlapping: the `Closure` type is `immutable` if no `use ()` nor `global` nor `static` variables are present
 * [ ] Executing logic on the result (`object|callable`) of a `@psalm-pure` context is not to be considered pure (https://psalm.dev/r/a1852660f6):
    ```php
    /**
     * @psalm-pure
     * @psalm-return callable() : void
     */
    function makeSomeStuff() : callable
    {
        return static function () {
            \var_dump('this closure is not pure');
        };
    }

    // expecting an error from this one - currently detects nothing
    /** @psalm-pure */
    function notReallyPure() : void
        makeSomeStuff()();
    }
    ```
 * [ ] Later, we probably need a way to document parameter and return types as `@psalm-pure`, sort of like a meta-interface that needs to be part of the type (https://psalm.dev/r/a2d34a695d - parse error):
    ```php
    /**
     * @psalm-pure
     * @psalm-return @psalm-pure callable() : int
     */
    function makeSomeStuff() : callable
    {
        return static function () {
            return 1;
        };
    }

    // no error expected 
    /** @psalm-pure */
    function notReallyPure() : int
    {
        return makeSomeStuff()();
    }
    ```
